03:25.839 --> 03:27.541
Thank you!

03:27.675 --> 03:29.977
(cheering, whistling)

03:55.769 --> 03:57.304
After 14 years of head-banging,

03:57.471 --> 04:00.107
Metallica bassist Jason Newsted
has quit the band,

04:00.274 --> 04:02.343
citing “private
and personal reasons

04:02.509 --> 04:04.345
<i>"and the physical damage that
I've done to myself</i>

04:04.511 --> 04:06.814
<i>over the years while playing
the music I love."</i>

04:06.981 --> 04:09.650
Metallica's management had no
comment when asked by MTV News

04:09.817 --> 04:11.518
if there's a replacement waiting
in the wings.

04:11.685 --> 04:12.786
But the band is still scheduled

04:12.953 --> 04:14.588
to begin recording
a new album this spring.

04:14.722 --> 04:17.591
<i>That's the news for now.
Stay tuned for more news...</i>

04:17.725 --> 04:18.926
<i>PHIL TOWLE: I</i> mean, <i>I think
everybody understands</i>

04:19.059 --> 04:20.995
<i>the concept of
trusting instincts.</i>

04:21.161 --> 04:22.663
That's getting to a place where

04:22.830 --> 04:25.833
you don't let egos and let...

04:26.000 --> 04:27.635
stuff get in the way of...

04:27.801 --> 04:28.969
artistic expression.

04:29.136 --> 04:30.004
<i>You know?</i>

04:30.170 --> 04:31.372
<i>So, I mean, this...</i>

04:31.538 --> 04:32.973
<i>I mean, do you want to say
any more about that?</i>

04:33.140 --> 04:34.141
<i>'Cause, I mean, I think
everybody understands that...</i>

04:34.308 --> 04:35.376
<i>I met Metallica through</i>

04:35.542 --> 04:38.379
<i>Q-Prime Management
after having seen me</i>

04:38.545 --> 04:39.680
<i>work with another
band of theirs.</i>

04:39.847 --> 04:40.681
<i>When they called and said</i>

04:40.848 --> 04:41.815
<i>that Metallica...</i>

04:41.982 --> 04:43.484
<i>with Jason, uh,</i>

04:43.651 --> 04:46.487
<i>announcing that he was
exiting the group...</i>

04:46.654 --> 04:47.855
<i>needed to take a look at itself</i>

04:48.022 --> 04:49.356
<i>and say, "Well,
what's going on here?</i>

04:49.523 --> 04:51.859
<i>We've lost touch with our
personal relationships."</i>

04:52.026 --> 04:54.228
And face some of the issues that

04:54.395 --> 04:58.632
I think Q-Prime felt
that they were headed for.

04:58.766 --> 05:00.167
You know, we haven't
really worked together

05:00.334 --> 05:01.802
for almost nine months.

05:01.935 --> 05:05.706
When we were talking a couple
of days ago about whether...

05:05.873 --> 05:07.508
you know, if we wanted
to do this film or not...

05:07.675 --> 05:10.044
I was wondering if

05:10.210 --> 05:12.513
having these guys in here...

05:12.680 --> 05:13.714
would affect that.

05:13.881 --> 05:15.249
Yeah. 'Cause I'm just...

05:15.416 --> 05:16.717
...there's an intimacy
that you get

05:16.884 --> 05:19.486
when it's just a few
people in the room

05:19.620 --> 05:21.655
and I'm just wondering if
that's going to get lost.

05:21.789 --> 05:24.325
If we're gonna go back to
sort of, like,

05:24.458 --> 05:26.026
battling each other

05:26.193 --> 05:28.028
and trying to be,
like, all strong and...

05:28.195 --> 05:29.196
What intimacy?

05:29.363 --> 05:30.331
What the fuck are you
talking about?

05:30.464 --> 05:32.166
(laughs)

05:32.299 --> 05:34.034
TOWLE:
I think, to me,

05:34.201 --> 05:35.569
it's not going to be
a matter of whether

05:35.736 --> 05:37.604
the cameras are in play,

05:37.771 --> 05:39.039
but whether or not

05:39.206 --> 05:40.207
you guys are free enough

05:40.374 --> 05:43.444
to risk being seen
by other people.

05:50.217 --> 05:52.186
(intro playing)

06:08.769 --> 06:11.472
HARMON:
We're here, uh, in the Presidio

06:11.638 --> 06:13.207
in San Francisco,

06:13.340 --> 06:15.275
and this is going
to be the location

06:15.442 --> 06:18.545
where Metallica is gonna start
recording their next album.

06:18.679 --> 06:21.415
<i>BOB ROCK". We decided that we
didn't want to go back</i>

06:21.582 --> 06:23.917
<i>into a studio again
and do kind of like</i>

06:24.084 --> 06:25.419
<i>the same thing
we had done before.</i>

06:25.586 --> 06:26.987
We had to kind of...

06:27.154 --> 06:28.389
change things up.

06:28.522 --> 06:30.257
And this is one of the things
that we talked about,

06:30.424 --> 06:32.426
<i>was to go into a space</i>

06:32.593 --> 06:33.761
<i>that's not a studio,</i>

06:33.927 --> 06:35.329
<i>bring in kind of like
a portable studio,</i>

06:35.496 --> 06:36.330
<i>or a makeshift studio...</i>

06:36.497 --> 06:37.631
That's good.

06:37.798 --> 06:40.401
...and basically make
the situation uncomfortable.

06:40.534 --> 06:42.169
<i>HARMON: You know, don't buy
new furniture,</i>

06:42.336 --> 06:43.303
<i>don't paint the walls.</i>

06:43.470 --> 06:44.438
<i>Don't do anything.</i>

06:44.605 --> 06:46.006
<i>Just keep it Spartan,
keep it crude.</i>

06:47.608 --> 06:49.176
<i>They're such a success
that you can get comfortable.</i>

06:49.343 --> 06:50.944
<i>I don't think they want
to be comfortable.</i>

06:51.111 --> 06:52.980
Well, there's definitely
a vibe in here.

06:53.147 --> 06:54.448
They've got a lot of attitude
and I think

06:54.615 --> 06:56.650
they want it to come out
on this next album.

06:59.286 --> 07:00.654
How did you approach
this record differently?

07:00.821 --> 07:01.855
I mean, did you
talk about things,

07:02.022 --> 07:03.123
did you have ideas,
key words,

07:03.290 --> 07:04.491
things like that
that you wanted to put across

07:04.658 --> 07:05.692
before you
actually started

07:05.859 --> 07:07.694
putting the whole
thing together?

07:07.861 --> 07:09.263
Well, ego was
a big one.

07:09.396 --> 07:11.198
Uh, coming in here

07:11.365 --> 07:13.267
and not bringing
a riff,

07:13.400 --> 07:14.368
not bringing
a song,

07:14.535 --> 07:16.203
not bringing a title.
Nothing.

07:16.370 --> 07:18.305
Uh, me and James

07:18.472 --> 07:20.340
did not meet
somewhere else

07:20.507 --> 07:22.810
and come in here
with material.

07:22.976 --> 07:24.511
With songs.
With music.

07:24.678 --> 07:26.880
This time, we all got in a room

07:27.047 --> 07:28.348
and just started playing.

07:28.515 --> 07:29.683
And that's how we wrote songs.

07:29.850 --> 07:32.619
(playing a riff)

07:34.221 --> 07:37.057
<i>BOB ROCK: The idea is,
it should sound like</i>

07:37.224 --> 07:39.526
a band getting together in
a garage for the first time.

07:39.693 --> 07:41.395
(guitar playing)

07:41.562 --> 07:43.330
Only the band's Metallica.

07:43.497 --> 07:45.866
<i>II'</i>

08:03.350 --> 08:05.719
JAMES <i>HETFIELD:
I really like going fast.</i>

08:07.421 --> 08:10.858
<i>Just go off and meditate
in the wind, you know?</i>

08:11.024 --> 08:12.359
<i>As corny as it sounds,
it-it works,</i>

08:12.526 --> 08:13.894
<i>and it feels good.
It's a good way to...</i>

08:14.061 --> 08:15.929
<i>just let the weight
of the world off</i>

08:16.096 --> 08:18.665
<i>every once in a while.</i>

08:18.799 --> 08:20.667
<i>It is it is kind of
strange being...</i>

08:20.801 --> 08:23.770
you know, like a famous guy.

08:23.937 --> 08:25.906
You know.

08:28.308 --> 08:29.877
This is... this is part of me

08:30.043 --> 08:31.378
that's trying to be unfamous,
I guess.

08:31.545 --> 08:35.883
<i>But it's also
go-against-the-rules attitude.</i>

08:36.049 --> 08:37.384
<i>You know, is this
some big pose?</i>

08:37.551 --> 08:39.352
I mean, yes, this is a pose.

08:39.486 --> 08:40.888
I mean, am I driving
down the street

08:41.054 --> 08:42.356
to not get noticed
in this thing?

08:42.489 --> 08:44.725
<i>I mean, rebellious is
kind of what this says,</i>

08:44.892 --> 08:46.727
(laughing):
<i>I would</i> say.

08:46.894 --> 08:49.396
(engine revs)

08:49.563 --> 08:51.698
<i>II'</i>

08:58.071 --> 08:59.139
Have you got
a plug in here?

08:59.306 --> 09:01.542
Wait, wait, wait, so what
exactly are you doing?

09:01.675 --> 09:03.110
ROCK: Well, you'll just
hold it above the...

09:03.277 --> 09:05.078
the pick ups.
HAMMETT: Oh, okay.

09:05.245 --> 09:07.114
I gotcha.

09:07.281 --> 09:09.216
(guitar wails) HETFIELD: Yeah!

09:14.588 --> 09:16.623
HETFIELD:
♪ Give me fuel, give me fire ♪

09:16.790 --> 09:18.058
♪ Give me that which I desire ♪

09:18.191 --> 09:19.726
♪ Give me fuel, give me fire ♪

09:19.860 --> 09:23.263
♪ Give me that which I desire ♪

09:23.430 --> 09:26.900
♪ Give me fuel, give me fire,
give me that which I desire ♪

09:30.337 --> 09:31.438
ULRICH:
Uh, I got some bad news.

09:31.605 --> 09:32.439
Gonna have to, uh...

09:32.606 --> 09:33.607
HETFIELD:
Change the lyrics?

09:33.774 --> 09:34.608
(Hetfield laughs)

09:34.775 --> 09:35.742
(buzzing)

09:35.876 --> 09:37.477
I like this thing, Bob.

09:37.644 --> 09:38.946
ROCK: What?
I like this thing.

09:39.112 --> 09:40.414
<i>II'</i>

09:45.619 --> 09:48.121
<i>ULRICH:
I used to kid myself that</i>

09:48.288 --> 09:50.857
<i>art was my great escape
away from music.</i>

09:51.024 --> 09:52.826
<i>And I think I've become
increasingly aware</i>

09:52.993 --> 09:55.095
<i>that my interest in art,</i>

09:55.228 --> 09:57.598
<i>music, and Metallica...</i>

09:57.731 --> 09:59.833
<i>is not separate from anything.</i>

10:00.000 --> 10:02.135
You know, what does he feel
that there's enough of that...

10:02.302 --> 10:03.337
kind of gold thing?

10:03.503 --> 10:05.639
How come there isn't...

10:05.806 --> 10:08.008
another 20 strokes

10:08.175 --> 10:09.810
up in that black area up there
where it's...

10:09.977 --> 10:11.278
where it's kind of bare?

10:11.411 --> 10:12.879
Where are the starting points
and where are the end points?

10:13.046 --> 10:14.147
Do you know what I mean?

10:14.314 --> 10:16.350
When's a song done?

10:16.516 --> 10:17.684
What the fuck
does that mean anyway?

10:17.851 --> 10:18.986
"Done."

10:19.152 --> 10:21.221
When's a record done?
(little boy shouting)

10:21.388 --> 10:22.689
You know, when...
where does a record start?

10:22.856 --> 10:23.824
Where does it end?

10:23.991 --> 10:25.525
Urn, where does
the process start?

10:25.692 --> 10:26.827
Where the process end?

10:26.994 --> 10:28.495
All that type of stuff.
Do you know what I mean?

10:28.662 --> 10:29.963
MYLES:
Daddy!

10:30.097 --> 10:30.964
It's really interesting.

10:31.098 --> 10:32.733
Yes, sweetie?

10:32.899 --> 10:34.868
<i>II'</i>

10:38.505 --> 10:39.506
I don't, I don't feel
anything great there.

10:39.673 --> 10:40.907
ROCK
Yeah, he didn't know...

10:41.074 --> 10:43.010
HAMMET: I don't think it's
that great a riff, either.

10:43.176 --> 10:44.711
How do you hear the riff, then?
ROCK I like that

10:44.878 --> 10:46.480
(singing riff)

10:46.613 --> 10:47.814
and then...
Mm-hmm.

10:47.948 --> 10:49.249
(both singing riff)
HAMMETT: Yeah.

10:49.416 --> 10:51.585
(all playing the riff)

11:06.299 --> 11:08.168
(seagull squawks)

11:08.301 --> 11:09.736
HAMMETT:
<i>In</i> nine days,

11:09.903 --> 11:13.206
it'll be my two-year
anniversary of surfing.

11:13.373 --> 11:16.743
<i>It's taken the place of a lot
of bad things in my life.</i>

11:16.910 --> 11:18.445
<i>So I-l basically</i>

11:18.612 --> 11:21.048
<i>stopped doing the drugs
that I was doing</i>

11:21.214 --> 11:23.950
<i>and, uh... cut way back
on my drinking.</i>

11:24.117 --> 11:26.053
You can't surf
when you're hung over.

11:26.219 --> 11:28.355
You can't surf if you've
been up all night...

11:28.488 --> 11:30.357
well, at least I can't.
(laughs)

11:32.659 --> 11:34.061
<i>There's a-a sort of</i>

11:34.227 --> 11:37.064
<i>individualism, also,
about surfing that I like.</i>

11:37.230 --> 11:38.298
<i>I mean...</i>

11:38.465 --> 11:40.400
when it...
when it's your moment, man,

11:40.567 --> 11:42.569
that's your moment
and yours alone.

11:42.736 --> 11:44.771
<i>And no one can help you.</i>

11:44.938 --> 11:45.906
(laughs)

11:48.275 --> 11:49.309
(laughs triumphantly)

11:50.410 --> 11:51.378
(trolley bell clangs)

11:53.113 --> 11:54.281
<i>ULRICH:
For all intents and purposes,</i>

11:54.448 --> 11:55.982
<i>we-we go into this record</i>

11:56.149 --> 11:57.751
<i>completely equal.</i>

11:57.918 --> 11:59.653
Everybody contributing

11:59.820 --> 12:01.555
just as much on the lyric front

12:01.688 --> 12:04.624
as James contributing
with drum parts and...

12:04.791 --> 12:06.293
As soon as you started
talking about that,

12:06.460 --> 12:08.061
I just, like...

12:08.195 --> 12:09.429
(laughs)
HETFIELD: Yeah. Yeah.

12:09.596 --> 12:10.764
You flash back now?

12:10.931 --> 12:11.965
(laughs)
Well...

12:12.132 --> 12:14.468
You want to hear
it with vocals?

12:14.634 --> 12:15.969
BOB ROCK: I said...
Go sing it.

12:16.136 --> 12:19.005
<i>ROCK". You guys had some rules
about that before.</i>

12:19.172 --> 12:21.007
Quite frankly,
I don't give a fuck.

12:21.174 --> 12:22.943
I'm tired of arguing.

12:23.110 --> 12:24.778
<i>ROCK". You couldn't talk
about his lyrics,</i>

12:24.945 --> 12:27.280
<i>therefore, he couldn't talk
about your drumming.</i>

12:27.447 --> 12:28.448
<i>ULRICH:
Right. (laughs)</i>

12:28.615 --> 12:29.616
ROCK: Do you know
what I mean? And...

12:29.783 --> 12:31.985
you and him did the solos...
(Ulrich laughs)

12:32.152 --> 12:33.987
...so you weren't allowed
to comment on the solos.

12:34.154 --> 12:35.589
Do you know
what I mean?

12:35.722 --> 12:37.124
There was, like, rules.
HETFIELD: Oh, definitely.

12:37.290 --> 12:38.258
Are you telling me that...

12:38.391 --> 12:40.193
that those boundaries
are gone now?

12:40.360 --> 12:42.696
(all chuckle)

12:45.532 --> 12:47.868
<i>ULRICH:
In the past, what we did was</i>

12:48.034 --> 12:50.003
<i>started with a bunch of ideas</i>

12:50.170 --> 12:52.005
<i>existing on tape
from everybody.</i>

12:52.172 --> 12:53.507
<i>Then me and James
would sit down</i>

12:53.673 --> 12:55.175
<i>and turn those ideas into songs</i>

12:55.342 --> 12:56.977
and then we would tell
the rest of the band

12:57.144 --> 12:59.312
what to play and when to play
and how to play it.

12:59.479 --> 13:00.647
<i>There was never any...</i>

13:00.814 --> 13:02.215
<i>just other ways of doing it.</i>

13:02.382 --> 13:03.984
<i>HETFIELD:
You know, it's just</i>

13:04.151 --> 13:06.987
<i>a whole new thing for me.</i>

13:07.154 --> 13:10.190
<i>You know, writing
in front of everybody...</i>

13:10.357 --> 13:12.225
<i>'cause I've always just gone
into my own head</i>

13:12.392 --> 13:13.860
<i>and wrote stuff down</i>

13:14.027 --> 13:15.562
<i>instead of taking
things from outside</i>

13:15.729 --> 13:17.697
<i>and putting them down.</i>

13:19.733 --> 13:21.034
ROCK: You know,
I was thinking this is like,

13:21.201 --> 13:23.203
"these are the hands
that da-da-da-da,

13:23.370 --> 13:25.338
this is the face that
da-da-da-da,"

13:25.505 --> 13:26.473
so it's like...

13:26.606 --> 13:28.141
Building a Frankenstein
or something?

13:28.275 --> 13:29.376
Yeah.
Pretty much.

13:29.543 --> 13:30.377
Building what?

13:30.544 --> 13:31.678
A Frankenstein.

13:31.845 --> 13:33.413
This is the top of my
head that's flat...

13:33.580 --> 13:35.415
(laughs)
These are my bolts...

