♪ Like it only rains on me ♪

33:04.183 --> 33:08.854
♪ God, it feels... ♪

33:09.021 --> 33:11.390
<i>TORBEN ULRICH: I think it's easy
to see that, in those days,</i>

33:11.557 --> 33:13.192
<i>Metallica brought a kind of</i>

33:13.359 --> 33:15.928
<i>physicality to rock 'n' roll.</i>

33:17.363 --> 33:20.366
Let's say the Beatles,
the Rolling Stones,

33:20.532 --> 33:22.034
you know, and all that

33:22.201 --> 33:23.669
inspired some of the British

33:23.802 --> 33:25.838
rock music that then
developed after that.

33:25.971 --> 33:28.941
And, let's say,
the metal music and...

33:29.108 --> 33:32.177
and Led Zeppelin and Black
Sabbath and all of that.

33:32.311 --> 33:34.346
And then,
out of that again,

33:34.480 --> 33:36.048
then, let's say,
then came Lars

33:36.215 --> 33:37.916
and all of that
and being...

33:38.083 --> 33:38.951
So I think that...

33:39.118 --> 33:40.552
that they have certainly, uh,

33:40.719 --> 33:42.221
a place in all of that, I think.

33:42.388 --> 33:45.224
Lars had a very good
vision, at the time,

33:45.391 --> 33:48.060
of where he saw

33:48.227 --> 33:50.462
that particular... you know,
the metal music going,

33:50.629 --> 33:51.764
because he could see

33:51.930 --> 33:54.199
with European
ears and eyes, maybe.

33:54.333 --> 33:57.970
Yes, actually. Don't you
feel that it's great for you

33:58.137 --> 34:01.907
to have your father's
perspective <i>on...</i>

34:02.074 --> 34:03.776
on who you are and
what you're doing?

34:03.942 --> 34:05.577
I think that's
incredible, and it's...

34:05.744 --> 34:07.646
you know, talk about
the lineage...

34:07.813 --> 34:08.981
which we did.

34:09.148 --> 34:10.149
We talked a little bit
about your grandfather...

34:10.315 --> 34:11.483
I mean, it's very
difficult to admit it,

34:11.650 --> 34:12.885
especially with him
standing next to me.

34:13.018 --> 34:15.087
I... it's easier
to talk about

34:15.254 --> 34:17.255
when he's not
in my presence.

34:17.422 --> 34:18.556
But, urn...

34:18.690 --> 34:21.060
of course it is.

34:21.193 --> 34:22.494
Yeah.
What would you...

34:22.661 --> 34:24.163
what would you
say in private?

34:24.329 --> 34:25.164
To who?

34:25.330 --> 34:26.598
To anybody,
without him here.

34:26.764 --> 34:27.733
Say it.

34:27.866 --> 34:28.900
You know, what...
what would it be?

34:29.034 --> 34:30.235
Well, I mean,
I've already said it

34:30.369 --> 34:31.235
to you countless times.

34:31.370 --> 34:33.338
Well, have you
said it to him?

34:35.040 --> 34:37.109
(laughs)
Urn...

34:37.275 --> 34:38.110
TOWLE:
What is it that you...

34:38.277 --> 34:39.110
you-you brought it up.

34:39.277 --> 34:40.279
I didn't bring it up.

34:40.446 --> 34:42.114
What is it you feel you've said

34:42.281 --> 34:43.649
that you're not saying now?

34:43.815 --> 34:44.783
You <i>can...</i> you know... ULRICH:
I think maybe in some ways,

34:44.949 --> 34:45.851
some of the, urn...

34:46.018 --> 34:47.085
TOWLE:
To me, that's...

34:47.219 --> 34:49.321
A fear of status quo

34:49.487 --> 34:51.489
comes a little bit from
this direction over here.

34:51.657 --> 34:53.692
I think that, um...

34:53.859 --> 34:55.661
I mean there's
nothing worse

34:55.828 --> 34:57.763
than when I have to go to him
and play the new record

34:57.896 --> 35:00.432
and know there's something
on there that sucks.

35:00.566 --> 35:01.867
And he can see
right through that

35:02.034 --> 35:03.635
in two and a half
seconds flat.

35:03.802 --> 35:05.771
<i>II'</i>

35:15.314 --> 35:22.955
<i>♪ I... want to</i> live <i> ♪</i>

35:25.357 --> 35:29.495
♪ I... ♪

35:29.661 --> 35:35.400
♪ Want to live... ♪

35:41.340 --> 35:42.307
ULRICH:
Comments on that one?

35:45.277 --> 35:46.345
TORBEN:
I would say...

35:46.512 --> 35:48.013
You know,
if-if you said...

35:48.180 --> 35:51.917
"if you were our advisor,

35:52.084 --> 35:53.085
what would you say?"

35:53.252 --> 35:54.853
Then I would say, "Delete that."

35:55.020 --> 35:56.922
You know?

35:57.089 --> 35:58.490
(chuckles nervously)

35:58.624 --> 36:00.692
I mean...
I mean, I don't know

36:00.859 --> 36:01.760
for you guys.

36:01.927 --> 36:03.428
For-for me, it doesn't cut it.

36:03.595 --> 36:05.063
You know?

36:05.230 --> 36:06.198
Huh.

36:06.365 --> 36:07.533
But, uh...
That's interesting.

36:07.699 --> 36:09.101
I mean, it's interesting,
you know, now... Yeah.

36:09.268 --> 36:11.203
I mean, other than the people
involved here... Yeah...

36:11.370 --> 36:12.437
...the only other people
who've heard

36:12.604 --> 36:14.039
any of this music
is Cliff Burnstein.

36:14.206 --> 36:15.174
Yeah.

36:15.307 --> 36:16.375
When Cliff Burnstein heard that,

36:16.542 --> 36:18.177
he thought that should
open the record.

36:18.310 --> 36:19.178
Yeah?
(laughs)

36:19.311 --> 36:21.013
I mean, that
could well be.

36:21.146 --> 36:22.381
But I...

36:22.548 --> 36:24.883
I'm pretty sure that...

36:25.050 --> 36:27.052
that I really... that...

36:27.219 --> 36:28.387
I really...

36:28.554 --> 36:29.721
I-I really don't think so.

36:29.888 --> 36:30.722
(laughing):
You know?

36:30.889 --> 36:32.191
(both laughing)

36:32.324 --> 36:33.292
I really
don't think so.

36:34.726 --> 36:35.561
Right.

36:35.727 --> 36:36.762
TORBEN:
For me, that...

36:36.929 --> 36:38.764
that doesn't sound
right or something.

36:38.931 --> 36:40.299
You know.

36:40.465 --> 36:42.568
Unless I'm... a guy

36:42.734 --> 36:43.702
that's kind of, uh,

36:43.835 --> 36:45.103
shouting in some...

36:45.270 --> 36:46.705
some kind of echo chamber.
(laughs)

36:48.240 --> 36:50.209
(laughing)

36:55.414 --> 36:57.249
Huh?
It's a joke.

36:57.416 --> 36:58.917
Yeah.

36:59.084 --> 37:01.053
<i>II'</i>

37:05.290 --> 37:07.726
(indistinct talking)

37:17.336 --> 37:19.638
TOWLE: So I think one of
our responsibilities here

37:19.805 --> 37:21.640
is to act like a band

37:21.807 --> 37:23.609
<i>that's still continuing.
We're going on.</i>

37:23.775 --> 37:24.943
<i>We're doing our exploring.</i>

37:25.110 --> 37:26.445
<i>We're exploring ourselves
individually,</i>

37:26.612 --> 37:28.447
we're exploring
our relationships.

37:28.614 --> 37:29.681
And, uh, we
really need to...

37:29.848 --> 37:32.784
get together,
talk about this,

37:32.951 --> 37:34.786
act like the band exists...

37:34.953 --> 37:36.188
because it does exist.

37:36.355 --> 37:38.523
And if we don't do that,

37:38.690 --> 37:41.026
then we are

37:41.193 --> 37:43.795
the co-producers
of the process

37:43.962 --> 37:45.530
slipping off the planet.

37:46.965 --> 37:49.334
It is a bit of
a shit sandwich, though.

37:49.501 --> 37:51.603
What is it...

37:51.737 --> 37:52.971
the unraveling of a band?

37:53.138 --> 37:54.139
(laughs)

37:54.306 --> 37:55.641
And then there were two?

37:55.807 --> 37:57.476
HAMMET: Yeah. You know...
ROCK: So...

37:57.643 --> 38:00.012
Uh... a good friend of mine

38:00.178 --> 38:01.280
phoned me.

38:01.413 --> 38:02.781
And he knew where James was.

38:02.914 --> 38:03.815
ULRICH:
Really?

38:03.982 --> 38:05.517
Yeah. He couldn't
even imagine

38:05.684 --> 38:09.454
James doing anything
for six months.

38:12.524 --> 38:14.960
I'm prepared for the worst.

38:15.093 --> 38:17.529
I'm pretty confident that,
you know,

38:17.696 --> 38:20.499
we will come together
when the time is right.

38:20.666 --> 38:22.134
But...

38:22.267 --> 38:25.671
knowing when that time
will come...

38:25.837 --> 38:28.006
or not knowing
when that time will come

38:28.173 --> 38:30.575
is very, very uncomfortable.

38:30.742 --> 38:35.047
ULRICH: I hope that,
at some point, he will

38:35.213 --> 38:38.050
come back and try and finish

38:38.216 --> 38:40.185
the making of this record.

38:41.386 --> 38:42.854
If...

38:51.263 --> 38:52.698
If he walked away
from Metallica,

38:52.864 --> 38:55.033
I'm not sure that
it would surprise me.

38:55.200 --> 38:57.169
<i>II'</i>

39:05.977 --> 39:10.282
♪ Say your prayers little one,
don't forget, my son ♪

39:10.449 --> 39:13.885
♪ To include everyone ♪

